soft-delete vs hard-delete bloat benchmark
PostgreSQL 16.14 (Debian 16.14-1.pgdg13+1) on aarch64-unknown-linux-gnu
params: cycles=50 insert_batch=5000 remove_batch=4000 latency_iterations=300 seed=1234

EXPERIMENT 1  table/index bloat under churn (50 cycles, 5.2s)
  hard_delete_orders  total=20.81 MB  table=8.62 MB  secondary_index=7.69 MB  live=50000  dead=0
  soft_delete_orders  total=59.64 MB  table=41.85 MB  secondary_index=9.65 MB  live=242764  dead=0
  ratio (soft/hard): total=2.87x  table=4.86x  secondary_index=1.26x

EXPERIMENT 2  query latency after bloat accumulated
  hard_delete_orders   pk_lookup    p50=  0.2627ms  p95=  0.7703ms  p99=  1.3674ms  mean=  0.3265ms
  hard_delete_orders   active_rows  p50=  4.8926ms  p95=  8.0662ms  p99= 10.5100ms  mean=  5.3501ms
  soft_delete_orders   pk_lookup    p50=  0.2206ms  p95=  0.2783ms  p99=  0.3044ms  mean=  0.2316ms
  soft_delete_orders   active_rows  p50=  0.3168ms  p95=  0.3785ms  p99=  0.8470ms  mean=  0.3298ms
  active_rows p99 ratio (soft/hard) = 0.08x

EXPERIMENT 3  partial index fix
  soft_delete_original_index   p50=  0.2962ms  p95=  1.2412ms  p99=  3.4540ms  rows_removed_by_filter=2      index_size=9880.0 KB
  soft_delete_partial_index    p50=  0.2635ms  p95=  0.3900ms  p99=  0.7293ms  rows_removed_by_filter=0      index_size=1112.0 KB
  hard_delete_baseline         p50=  5.0807ms  p95=  7.2622ms  p99= 11.5347ms  rows_removed_by_filter=0      index_size=7872.0 KB
  partial index is 8.9x smaller than the full index (1112.0 KB vs 9880.0 KB)
  active_rows p99 improves 4.74x after adding the partial index (3.4540ms -> 0.7293ms)

